    "reasoning": "To implement the TopModule as described, the key is to detect any edge on each bit of the 8-bit input and output a delayed version. Each output bit of anyedge should be high one cycle after a transition. For edge detection, the standard approach is to store the previous input and compare. Since the output triggers on the next cycle, we need a two-stage pipeline: current and previous inputs. For each bit, anyedge[i] is 1 if current[i] != previous[i], and that result is delayed by one cycle to match the requirement. Using non-blocking assignments in sequential always blocks to update the stages. All signals should be declared as logic with appropriate widths. Initialization is done via initial blocks to avoid X. Ports are defined correctly with 8-bit in and 8-bit anyedge. No state machines or resets required unless specified, which they aren't. So two registers, prev_in and curr_in, each 8 bits. prev_in holds the previous value, curr_in the current. Edge detected as XOR between them, stored in next_edge, then delayed by one clock to produce the output. Thus, assign anyedge = delayed_edge.",
    "module": "module TopModule (\n    input logic clk,\n    input logic [7:0] in,\n    output logic [7:0] anyedge\n);\n\n    logic [7:0] prev_in;\n    logic [7:0] curr_in;\n    logic [7:0] edge_detected;\n    logic [7:0] delayed_edge;\n\n    // Initialize previous inputs to avoid X\n    initial begin\n        prev_in = 8'b0;\n        curr_in = 8'b0;\n    end\n\n    // Sequential logic: track current and previous input\n    always @(posedge clk) begin\n        prev_in <= curr_in;\n        curr_in <= in;\n    end\n\n    // Combinational edge detection (XOR each bit)\n    assign edge_detected = curr_in ^ prev_in;\n\n    // Delay the edge detection by one cycle\n    always @(posedge clk) begin\n        delayed_edge <= edge_detected;\n    end\n\n    // Output assignment\n    assign anyedge = delayed_edge;\n\nendmodule"
