    "reasoning": "The solution involves creating a module TopModule with inputs clk (positive edge triggered) and 8-bit in, and output anyedge which detects any edge change in each bit of 'in' by registering the input twice. The first registered value (in1) captures the previous state, and the output is the XOR between 'in' and in1, indicating changes. For each bit, anyedge bit is set when a transition occurs, and it remains high for one cycle after the edge. The code uses two registers, in1 and in2 (or in1 and in2), to track two clock cycles. The anyedge logic is combinational using XOR between current and previous registered values. All ports and signals are declared as logic. No explicit reset since it's initialized in the registers with initial blocks, avoiding X. The code uses non-blocking assignments in sequential always blocks. Combinational always @(*) handles the XOR for each bit. Checked for syntax and RTL conventions.",
    "module": "module TopModule (input logic clk, input logic [7:0] in, output logic [7:0] anyedge);\n\n    // Registers to store previous values\n    logic [7:0] in1, in2;\n\n    // Sequential logic to update registers on clock edge\n    always @(posedge clk) begin\n        in1 <= in;\n        in2 <= in1;\n    end\n\n    // Combinational logic to detect any edge (change between current and previous clock cycle)\n    assign anyedge = in ^ in1;\n\nendmodule"
}
